Answer:
1. CORE RULE: The Designated Safeguarding Leads (DSLs) will monitor the unauthorised absence and take appropriate action. [Section 1.8]
2. EXCEPTIONS AND CONDITIONS:
    *   An immediate referral to the appropriate local social services is required only when a pupil has 10 consecutive school days of unexplained absence and all reasonable steps have been taken by the school to establish their whereabouts without success. [Section 1.8]
    *   Reasonable steps include telephone calls to all known contacts, e-mails to relatives, contact with other schools where siblings may be registered, enquiries to friends/neighbours etc. through school contacts, enquiries with any other service known to be involved with the pupil/family, and possible home visits where safe to do so, with all contacts and outcomes to be recorded on the pupil's file. [Section 1.8]
3. FINAL ANSWER: For 8 days of unexplained absence, the school's Designated Safeguarding Leads (DSLs) should monitor the unauthorised absence and take appropriate action. [Section 1.8] This appropriate action would involve taking reasonable steps to establish the student's whereabouts, such as telephone calls to all known contacts, e-mails to relatives, contacting other schools where siblings may be registered, making enquiries to friends/neighbours through school contacts, enquiring with any other service known to be involved with the pupil/family, and possibly conducting home visits where safe to do so, ensuring all contacts and outcomes are recorded on the pupil's file. [Section 1.8] An immediate referral to local social services is not yet required, as that action is specified for 10 consecutive days of unexplained absence after reasonable steps have been taken. [Section 1.8]

